%S A393598 69,130,209,386,663,1166,2037,3581,6256,10925,19320,34037,59316,
%T A393598 104597,182285,327365,575421,1023536
%N A393598 Maximum width of a simple perfect squared rectangle (SPSR) of order n.
%C A393598 A squared rectangle is "simple" if it contains no smaller squared rectangle, and "perfect" if all component squares have distinct sizes. The width is defined as the maximum dimension of the bounding rectangle.
%C A393598 The terms in this sequence were derived computationally by generating exhaustive sets of 3-connected planar graphs and mapping them to equivalent electrical networks (Brooks, Smith, Stone, and Tutte, 1940).
%C A393598 The exact absolute coordinates of every square are mapped topologically. The vertical bounding coordinates (heights) are verified using Kirchhoff's Voltage Law on the primary graph. The horizontal bounding coordinates (widths) are extracted by applying KVL across the faces of the corresponding dual graph.
%C A393598 Empirical observation: The maximum width of simple squared rectangles appears to scale asymptotically by a factor of approximately 1.77 (which is close to 16/9) per order n. Interestingly, the maximum width of Simple Imperfect Squared Squares (SISS, see [A393600 SISS]) scales by a factor of approximately 1.33 (close to 4/3) per order n. The rectangle growth factor is effectively the square of the square growth factor (since (4/3)^2 = 16/9). A theoretical intuition for this unproven relationship lies in the degrees of freedom: the dimensions of a squared square are strictly constrained (W = H), meaning its width scales proportionally to the square root of the maximum possible combinatorial area. A squared rectangle is unconstrained (W != H) and can elongate, allowing its maximum width to scale almost directly proportionally to the maximum area.
%D A393598 R. L. Brooks, C. A. B. Smith, A. H. Stone, and W. T. Tutte, The dissection of rectangles into squares, Duke Math. J. 7(1): 312-340 (1940).
%H A393598 Stuart E. Anderson, <a href="https://www.squaring.net/sq/sr/spsr/spsr.html">SPSR bouwkampcodes, tablecodes and postscript files for orders 9 to 22</a>, squaring.net.
%F A393598 Empirical observation: Logarithmic regression of the data up to n = 26 indicates an asymptotic growth scaling factor of approximately 1.76 to 1.77 per order. A curve fit suggests a(n) is approximately equal to exp(c*n+d) where c = 0.56. A formal proof of this asymptotic growth rate is not yet known.
%e A393598 For n = 9, a(9) = 69. This corresponds to the width of the well-known unique simple perfect squared rectangle of order 9. It has dimensions 69*61, and its Bouwkamp tablecode is 9 69 61 36 33 5 28 25 9 2 7 16. No simple perfect squared rectangle of order 9 can have a bounding dimension strictly greater than 69.
%Y A393598 Cf. A002839, A129947, A393600, A393599, A217148, A217149, A217154, A219766, A228953, A338861.
